Red Wine Exploration

Olivia Jonah

March 9, 2017

Introduction

This study is going to analyze wine data created by Paulo Cortez (Univ. Minho), Antonio Cerdeira, Fernando Almeida, Telmo Matos and Jose Reis (CVRVV) @ 2009. it shows how certain varibles can affect the quality of wine.

Univariate Plots Section

Database Structure

The dataset contains objetive and subjective quality data for 1599 red wines. There are a total of 14 variables, of which 13 are objective quality factors obtained from quality tests such as pH test, and 1 subjective factor that contains median expert evaluation score

Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

There are 1599 observation of wines in the dataset with 14 features . There is one categorical variable (quality) and the others are numerical variables indicating physical and chemical properties of the wine.

Other observations: The median quality is 6, which in the given scale (1-10) is a mediocre wine. The better wine in the sample has a score of 8, and the worst has a score of 3. The dataset is not balanced, that is, there are a more average wines than poor or excelent ones and this might prove challenging when designing a predicting algorithm.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

The main feature in the data is quality. Id like to determine which features determine the quality of wines.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your

investigation into your feature(s) of interest? The variables related to acidity (fixed, volatile, citric.acid and pH) might explain some of the variance. Maybe the different acid concentrations might alter the taste of the wine. Also, residual.sugar dictates how sweet a wine is and might also have an influence in taste.

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

A rating variable was created to improve the later visualizations.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did

you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?

Citric.acid stood out from the other distributions. It had (apart from some outliers) an retangularly looking distribution which given the wine quality distribution seems very unexpected.

Lets examine how each acid concentration affects pH.

Hmm surprisingly the acid concentration would has a positive correlation with pH. Maybe Simpsons Paradox?

to know if Simpsons Paradox is present, the regression coeficient is recalculated and the data is clusterized. the change in sign indicates that there is a lurking variable distorting the overall coefficient.

Since ph measures acid concentration using log scale, therefore the correlation between ph and the log of acid concentration is stronger. A linear model can help us tell the variance in ph level of the acidity variables

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One

Description One

This boxplot has different wine quality levels on its x-axis to the amount of alcohol on its y-axis. It clearly shows the increasing trend in the amount of alcohol when wine quality moves from lower level to higher level. The plot validates the concept of balancing taste attribute of good quality wine Box plots allow for comparison of data from different categories for easier, more effective decision-making.

Plot Two

Description Two

Using a scatterplot, this graph is aimed at identifying the unique content profile of quality wines by combining the two most important factors (sulphates and alcohol). The graph shows that as wine quality improves, with increase in alcohol and sulphate. To be able to ignore the outliers just eyeball the cloud of dots to locate a general trend, a scatter plot with regression line was used which helps me to make a discernable connection between the 3 things investigate dhere (alcohol, sulphates and quality) Combining the two High alcohol contents and high sulphate concentrations seem to produce better wines.

Plot Three

Description Three

Similiar to plot one, this plot uses a boxplot to show the different attributes across different quality levels. However, a minor improvement is made by changing the y-axis to show the error. Though small, the change leads to a much more clear comparison amongst all the levels. This change is driven by the idea that the higher quality has minimun error

Reflection

The wine data set contains information on the chemical properties of a selection of wines collected in 2009. It also includes sensorial data (wine ranking).

By looking at the individual distributions of the variables, to see how they relate to quality.

it was quick to notice the high concentration of wines in the middle ranges of the ranking, that is, average tasting wines.this raise eyebrows of a true correlation between the variables or maybe for lack of outlier. None of the correlations were above 0.7, however. The two variables that had relatively strong correlations were alcohol percentage and volatile acidity, but the individual correlations were not strong enough to make definitive conclusions with only bivariate analysis methods Citric acid stood out because as research shows citric acid is sometimes added to wines to boost overall acidity.

researching the subject

having said that the plots shows a strange distribution with some peaks but showing an almost rectangular distribution specially in the 0-0.5 range.

All of the other variables showed either an normal or long tailed looking distribution.

Next step was to see how the variables relate with each other to produce poor or better quality

This shows alcohol concentration, sulphates and the individual acid concentrations.

I also tried investigating the effect of each acid in the overall pH for the wine. I used scatterplots to explore the relationships graphically and also generated a linear model to check how much of pH the three variables accounted for.

Having a positive ph for correlation between acetic acid concentration suggests the presence of some lurking variable (Simpsons paradox) usingSimpsons package I confirmed that suspicion.

Finding out that the concentration of the three acids only account for less than half of the variance in pH, tells that there more components affecting acidity that were not measured.

Finally multivariate plots were used to find out interesting combinations of variables that might affect quality, and to confirm that density did not have an effect on quality whilst alcohol concentration constant.

the increase in quality has lesser error. The graphs adequately illustrate the factors that make good wines good and bad wines bad

For future studies, including malic and lactic acid would be interesting to mesure as these improves the taste. This data set may include storage time and storage method since these factors can influence the quality of wine as well. Also, maybe the relationship between price and quality of wine to investigate whether expensive wines lead to better quality. Wikipedia for example,

Maybe the dataset can have entry for the individuals judgemnt on the flavor, aroma (if can be clasiified), to make an interesting analysis.
